European inflation slipped into food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the dizzying rise in food prices.
The price increase in the month of November has been higher than expected in the 13 countries of the euro zone, registering - after 2.6 percent of the month of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Bureau of Statistics of the Union based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only 3 percent likely, Bloomberg reported.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut core interest on the pretext that the decline, along with rising commodity prices and reduced forced unemployment, would trigger a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "we have to negotiate" on inflation so that later it does not have to intervene on this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, registered in Germany, broke the record of twelve years; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation soared in the euro area as a result of galloping food and energy prices.
Wheat futures rose by 88 percent and soybean prices reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid for vegetable oil and dairy products in 2007.
The price of crude oil in the world market rose this year by 52 percent, reaching almost $100 a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, while for 2009 it will already fall to 1.9 percent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain in the next 3 or 4 months at around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to double interest rates in 2008.
Gallup predicts a government crisis
After a long stalemate, by early December the support of the Alliance of Young Democrats increased significantly, reaching its highest level since 2002, while the Gallup never experienced such a low level - 13 percent - in the case of the Socialists.
The difference in the case of the party’s safe voters – due to the greater steadfastness of the opposition voters – would mean support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) versus support of one-fifth for the socialists (20 percent).
According to the survey, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not even reach the limit necessary to have some parliamentary seat: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among the safe voters there are one percent more supporters on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous lowest point - it has never been so high, 41 percent of those who judged the economic situation of the country especially bad, while another 46 percent believe that the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the most hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
With regard to the coming year, the majority of the population expects the situation to deteriorate and only one tenth expects an improvement.
In December, 71 percent of those polled, higher than any previous Gallup poll, estimated that the President of the Government performs rather poorly than well his functions.
13 percent of those surveyed trust or trust Ferenc Gyurcs<0xC3><0xA1>ny very much, while Viktor Orb<0xC3><0xA1>n has the support of 38 percent of those surveyed.
54 percent of the population do not trust the head of government at all and 27 percent do not trust the president of the Alliance of Young Democrats.
One of the indicators of the configuration of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks that it is possible to control the discontent experienced in front of the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the October riots last year, 35 percent felt it would be desirable to keep the government and the head of government in power, this ratio is currently only 20 percent, while the relative majority (33 percent) believes that the only solution is holding new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the question about participation answered that they would surely participate and another 20 percent said that it is likely to participate.
By comparison, in "a general election to be held this Sunday" would participate safely only 55 percent of the population and another 15 percent believe likely participation. Based on the current intentions of the voters there is no doubt about the result of the popular consultation.
74 percent of the population would disapprove of the payment of study fees, 79 percent of the medical consultation service and 84 percent of the hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of study fees, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
The average price level increase of 16 percent was maintained by the hypermarkets of Budaörs’ gold trading triangle, with the difference that VAT has not been increased this year.
Article by Napi Gazdas<0xC3><0xA1>g
This year also saw an average increase of 16 percent in Budaörs’ gold trading triangle from the Napi newspaper’s usual Christmas basket, but in all hypermarkets there was a much higher growth than 1,000 HUF.
As prices in food supermarkets had already "fired" in December last year, so there was no drastic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below the nine thousand HUF, today they can not do it even for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF with a minimum of 91 HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10,573 HUF.
(in 2003 that basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a sharp increase in turkey breast fillet, walnut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Bureau of Statistics, although in the Auchan we have also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
Competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of Coca-Cola with a redeemable two-liter bottle cost less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
However, in Napi Auchan's basket it was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, with respect to last year’s Christmas prices, Cora increased by 15, while Tesco and Auchan increased by about 18 percent the prices listed in Napi’s basket.
Comparing the values of last year’s most expensive basket with that of this year’s cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so that during Christmas last year prices were felt the increase in VAT.
It was precisely this process that shattered commerce, supermarkets were visibly unable to make a decision on the price margin to be applied for each product and to calculate the effect of the change in prices on consumption.
(If the trader misplans the speed of circulation of a product, he may lose a significant profit on the margin that fits the sales volume.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, that the most expensive was higher with 1720 HUF than the value recorded in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only 844 HUF.
This year there were no such extremes, as the highest price has now been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased with 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic growth in prices in less than 20 months, in the hypermarkets the price of consumer essentials grew more than 30 percent.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some staple foods, recorded in the 12-month interval a price increase of more than 30 percent.
So, for example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of egg.)
According to the Napi basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product that was quite expensive already last year compared to the base, there was, in the worst case, only a 10 percent increase in prices.
According to all the indices, the suppliers of flour have a stronger position than those of egg, being able to impose the drastic increase of prices even to the multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain in the gold trading triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our experiences, most consumers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, taking by pallets the preserved food.
On Wednesday morning, the three stores formed large queues in front of the boxes because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that in the interior of the country the sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to the survey institutes because the revenues are below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in the case of household appliances.
In many hospitals you save with disinfectants
This year there have been several thousand infections in hospitals caused primarily by the misuse of antibiotics.
The hygienic circumstances prevailing in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds and the overload of staff do not favor the control of infections - says the doctor-head of department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals you save even with disinfectants.
A MRSA infection has not long ago been diagnosed in the traumatology department of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital earlier this year.
A person injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient shortly after had to return to the hospital as a result of the MRSA infection and since then it has not been possible to perform a major surgical intervention due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10 of this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multi-resistant agents have been registered in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System," said Karolina Böröcz, chief medical officer of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections caused by multi-resistant agents has certainly been recorded, for the rest there is no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
A third of humans carry the bacteria Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their nose without causing any disease.
Infections caused by AS (e.g., inflammation of the throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once over- or improperly applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics, turn into bacteria that are highly resistant to antibiotics and spread rapidly in inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or sepsis, in the first place to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with weakened body, to the elderly or to people of low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are common in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
“These patients are isolated, nurses take care of them in rubber gloves and masks, and there are the right antibiotics for their treatment,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are previously examined for the presence of MRSA in their body, but infection cannot even be prevented in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA hospital infections in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor for the prevention of formation and contagion with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the diseases that carry MRSA in their bodies.
In Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not fashionable.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most cases come to the public when already visible MRSA infections occur in the patient - said the doctor-head of the department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes stringent recommendations for the application of antibiotics in human medicine, and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological conditions.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less frequent in the case of walking patients or in basic care - said Karolina Böröcz.
It saves with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is spread from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, however also in this regard considerable faults are experienced in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted through drop transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately it can also be experienced - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals of less favorable economic situation you save with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater probability for infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where the appropriate preventive measures are followed, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the contagion of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so it is being fought against in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
The program appears to be successful, according to the data provided, infections with MRSA show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and that of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
