Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is admirable - the attention of the whole of Europe is directed towards that previously little-mentioned Balkan country.
What, where and who buys in the even cheaper EU market, which will quickly become more expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The preferred target for real estate acquisitions in Eastern Europe is without a doubt Bulgaria, with its cheap apartments on the ski slopes and chalets on the beaches.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while in Albena beaches, the "Golden Coast", the "Sun Coast", the ancient Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are looking for properties also in the surroundings of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to the analysts of Re/Max in Bulgaria, sooner or later also the central area of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will arouse the interest of real estate developers and more and more people will buy real estate in the especially cheap area of Rus.
In the same way, the capital Sofia can be attractive, the commercial and office spaces promise a quick recovery of the investment.
Bulgaria is on the best path to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe, and can thus be a prominent destination also during the other two seasons, in addition to summer and winter.
Therefore, cautious investors are already making their purchases, for example in the vicinity of Bansko.
In the opinion of analysts, those who buy real estate in Bulgaria, also strive to change their life and their way of life.
The majority of customers are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Also present are the Maltese and Cypriot promoters and traditionally there are many Russian customers on the beaches of the Black Sea and in the ski paradises.
Foreign customers can be classified into three groups - says Georgi Jankov, regional director of Re/Max in Bulgaria.
Those who intend to settle here buy new or renovated properties for a price between 50 and 100 thousand euros or old houses in poor condition between 5 and 15 thousand euros, to renovate them later.
They require good communication and access, in addition to the proximity of a large city, shops and usually a local doctor is important for them.
The second category consists of buyers of chalets (Bulgaria in December was included among the top 10 holiday destinations of the Germans).
The third group are real estate investors who make their purchases in the hope of profiting in the medium or long term.
The price of capital real estate is constantly growing, as demand is increasing.
Although in the European Union Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices, in the last five years these suffered an annual increase of 21 percent
The increase in the price of real estate considerably outweighs the growth in wages.
Fodor and the Six by Hundreds of Hungarians
As reported by the Minister of Environment and Hydrology G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor the meetings at the level of experts will end on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue negotiations at the level of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and policymakers from 192 countries around the world are discussing the Bali Roadmap for post-emissions efforts under the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
There are currently lively discussions on the subject between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that at the moment it does not want to negotiate on precise figures, although it tends to agree that compared to the situation in 1990, by 2020 the emission of greenhouse gases responsible for the greenhouse effect will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another major theme of the conference is whether or not industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological assistance to countries in need.
Agreement was also reached on the aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, foreseen in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member steering council, probably within the UN Global Environment Fund (GEF) - writes the "Piac és Profit".
The Six Hundreds of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of Environment and Hydrology G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing by 2020, from the 1990 level, its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent, regardless of whether or not the “post-2012 agreement” will be signed, and is willing to commit to reducing even by 30 percent if the world’s other major developed regions and developing countries are also willing to take commitments in accordance with their responsibility and capabilities.
G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor pointed out that the countries signatories to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol pledged to decrease by 5.2 percent, within this the then 15 EU member states pledged to meet an 8 percent decrease.
Hungary’s commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent over the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will comply with.
There is a lot at stake in Bali, since within two years the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed until after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments, assumed in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international system of emission reductions, the need for which was noted in its most recent report by the International Peace Conference.
With this, the reduction of emissions would be delayed and an increase of more than 2 <0xC2><0xB0> C in the average temperature of the Earth could not be prevented, a fact that according to scientists would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor publish footage of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
It was first the British Air Force (RAD) that took advantage of YouTube’s services: special units deployed in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos of their actions against the Taliban.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in Kandahar’s general operations corps, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
There are already 139 recordings from air force soldiers that have been uploaded to the Internet in this way and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered in the spring of 2007 under the name "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of actions perpetrated in both Iraq and Afghanistan, while both the Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos for recruitment purposes, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to introduce the public to the true objective of the presence of the British army abroad.
This type of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to conventional recruiting TV spots - defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC - instead, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the raison d'<0xC3><0xAA>tre of the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans made a video game.
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the suspiciously edited and censored recordings, there are also amateur videos in the distributor, for example about the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers speak at most of losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan have been uploaded to the Internet and numerous videos recorded in real operations, but the British military is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form of recruitment with free downloadable shooting video games called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers.
