The party is not always written with red numbers
In Hungary the law precisely defines the days that are written with red numbers on the calendar and has already become a widespread practice that around the holidays - which next year will be less - workdays are reorganized.
Even in the EU or in North America, the holidays are not unitary.
Hungarian laws make a difference between national holiday, state holiday and public holidays.
The festive days are fundamentally related to religious festivals and historical ephemeris.
We celebrate the New Year too: both the last day of the old year, and the first day of the new year is festive - the latter especially so that those who spent celebrating the old year can rest.
Throughout the year we have eleven festivities written with red numbers on the calendar.
It is a national holiday on March 15 in memory of the revolution of 1848 and on October 23, commemorative day of the revolution of 1956.
On August 20 we celebrate the founding of the State, on May 1st the feast of labor, on November 1st and 2nd we remember our deceased family and friends.
In addition, in our country there are two-day feasts: Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with a weekend, which is why it is often bridged when before or after the holiday there is only one working day.
In exchange for the extended weekends as well, during the previous Saturdays you can not be absent from work or school.
It is the minister of labour who regulates in his specific decree when it is necessary to work exactly in exchange for the day directly before or after the feast.
This legal rule is mandatory for all employers and their employees, as well as for employees and civil servants.
It is not mandatory for companies and service institutions that, due to their function, work uninterrupted even during the holidays.
This year the order of work can be altered only around the holidays of the end of the year: from December 24 practically stops life in the country, since according to experiences, most people "bridge" during the days between Christmas and the end of the year or take their holidays during these days.
Next year several of our parties will coincide with mid-week or weekends, so there will be fewer changes in working hours than this year.
First, the agenda around the Labor Day will be modified so that then, for four successive days, workers can rest.
Saturday, April 26 will be working day, so that in return Friday May 2 will be a festive day.
The other change relates to the holiday of October 23: on Saturday, October 18, work will have to be done instead of Friday, October 24.
On the other hand, the coming year during the holiday of the end of the year can be rested, since from December 24 will not work almost anywhere, even if the last day of the year is a Wednesday.
Six small deterrents to bitteren the lives of your colleagues
Emails that we forget to send, sound messages that we never receive, innocent lies that pass us unnoticed: all of them are part of our everyday "Folklore" at work.
Decide whether to adapt to minor discomforts or consciously avoid confusing situations that can irritate others.
Advice.
Sorry, I forgot to let you know you've been picked up from the marketing department," one of your colleagues said.
That's why you didn't go on a date?
At best he feels it and tries to fix the issue, maybe call the marketing department to tell them that he forgot to give you the message (this is the least common solution).
Most of the time the issue is resolved by apologizing.
Before proceeding to embarrassing explanations, it is worth meditating on the things with which you can bitteren the lives of your colleagues and consciously strive to avoid them.
Have you borrowed something that is not yours?
There’s nothing more irritating than when you want to pick up a document, an office tool, or your phone and you can’t find them.
Remember yesterday you put the stapler on the table, but by this morning it disappeared?
Do you find your lost pen on the table of one of your colleagues?
Do not take anything away from your colleagues without asking them, because they will rightly be angry at you for stealing their things.
Do not pick up envelopes or post-it from the office because it can be unpleasant when you need them immediately and run out ahead of time.
Gossip about your colleagues’ private lives?
There is no good solution to stop rumors that are already running.
Who, what are you doing and with whom?
Where and why?
Don’t pass on to everyone the information (conjectures) you have about your colleagues’ particular lives!
Don’t abuse your colleague’s trust when they share their most intimate secrets with you!
Buried in yourself what you have heard and do not gossip about your colleague in his absence, although others also know the things about him.
Are you taking sick leave unjustifiably?
When you call the office on the phone and say that you are sick and your head hurts unbearably, you feel bad or well, you feel that you prefer to rest on that day; think of others who must do your work, your impervious tasks, your work on term.
Don't bother your colleague!
If you already know in advance that the next day you will not go to the office or something may happen to you, so you should stay at home, tell them so that your colleagues or your boss do not have to face your absence the next day.
Gossip, laughter, phone calls
Are you involved in your work, but are you suddenly getting rid of the laughs of your colleagues?
Have you unintentionally heard a phone conversation that would have been better off not listening to it?
Do not bother your colleagues with your hums, chants, conversations aloud (less when you do them over their head), kicks, constant blasphemies, expressing your discontents aloud.
All of these can be annoying, even if they are not currently delving into a project (writing, planning, organization).
Do you blame others for a mistake?
Don’t blame others if you haven’t finished something on time, forgot to send an important letter or message!
Don’t allude to the chaos that eventually reigns in the office, or the noise that your colleagues make!
You must recognize if you have made a mistake that hurts others and you must repair the fault!
Ask how you can fix your fault!
Do you feel too much at home in the office?
Jogging and sneakers: very comfortable habit for the house, but not suitable for the office!
Do not wear a comfortable jogging even if your occupation allows it!
Don’t be messy, respect your colleagues and yourself wearing everyday, elegant and beautiful clothes when your occupation demands it!
