Banks want to solve the crisis
The U.S. Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian Central Banks decided to fight together against the financial market crisis.
More than a hundred billion dollars will be received through tenders in the Monetary Marking.
In these tenders, banks auction the interest rates for which they are able to lend money.
For example, the American Fed will bid for forty billion dollars, and then another twenty-four billion will be provided by the central banks of Europe and Switzerland.
After the September 11 attacks, it is the first time that central banks from different states have agreed on this coordinated process to protect and mitigate the consequences of the financial crisis.
"This step must solve the biggest economic problem, that is, the continued growth of the shortage of free capital that banks could lend," Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group wrote in his report for clients.
“This coordinated action by central banks likely reduced the recession in the United States from 65 percent to 50 percent,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already spent $60 billion on unpaid loans, especially in the United States.
Economists still expect billions in losses.
“Central banks must really be afraid of what awaits them when they decide to take this step,” said ABN Amro’s chief economist Kieran Davies.
“It seems that the situation is really bad,” he added.
Central banks fear that they will have the same problems in accessing loans and that they will have to lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the American economy into recession with different impacts on the growth of the world economy.
The central banks so decided, after they failed to reduce the so-called LIBOR rate, London’s interbank rate that is used for lending money in the interbank market.
This means that the banks constantly feared borrowing money even as the US, Canadian and British central banks lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
"It will have the same effect as another fall in interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some economists are not surprised that the step taken by the central banks contributes to igniting the crisis because it does not solve the fundamental problem that is the fall of the housing market in the United States.
