A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the destinies of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are openly accessible.
The 47 million file documents, stored on 27 km of shelves in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were hitherto not searchable only for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or his rightholders.
The eleven states in charge of its management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to seekers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening is effective since yesterday.
Sensitive Information
Historians’ access to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to search “particularly about the displacements of prisoners, the camp population and the health status of forced labourers,” explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, such as Germany, were opposed to the opening to the public of these nominative documents because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or detention orders established by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical purpose: to find the deported or subjected to compulsory labour and, eventually, to provide proof of their internment, in order to open the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees handle tens of thousands of individual petitions.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Antisemitism at the Technische Universität Berlin, said in 2006.
