However, it is too early for panic.
Delinquency and delinquency are at low levels.
According to Moody’s, a rating agency, in the third quarter the crime rate of 3.89% was almost one percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in the American Bankruptcy Law (2005) resulted in a sharp drop in bankruptcy applications, which in turn represent a large loss on credit cards; the number of applications (and therefore, delinquency) would be growing again, or it may happen that conditions for borrowers were getting worse.
The industry also reports strong payout rates, which show how much of its debts consumers pay each month.
And trust in credit cards and asset-backed securities is pretty strong, despite paralysis in other financial areas.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicts emission volumes for 2007 will be about 25% higher than last year.
The direct channels of crisis infection between subprime mortgages and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers like to charge debts to credit cards now that credit institutions are expiring.
But credit card issuers look more at the flow of liquidity than active securities, so falling prices don’t necessarily trigger a change in borrowers’ creditworthiness.
They can even work to outperform the issuers.
The incentives for consumers to continue to amortize the mortgage decrease if the properties are worth less than the loan value; and as a result, the payment of the card debt rises on the priority list.
Card issuers can also respond quickly and flexibly to the difficult conditions that mortgage lenders face by changing interest rates or altering credit balances.
That in theory should reduce the risk of a rapid asset tightening.
“We’re not going to wake up one day and re-evaluate all the loans,” says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
If a sudden subprime infection in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained decline are much more real.
