Venus: Earth's twin brother.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that until now had not been posed. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered lightning in the atmosphere and swirls at the poles, the same that also appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades, researchers suspected that lightning could exist on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus the rays shut off from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, tells Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous model of the origin of Urey-Miller life, lightning caused life on Earth: storms may have caused reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
On Venus it is not so: if there were ever life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface temperatures of 500<0xC2><0xB0>C reign, oscillating in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
"Possibly, Venus is an Earth's 'devil' twin, but it's still a twin," Russell said.
The main goal of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so Earth-like in mass and size, has evolved so differently.
Since there were no special missions since the 1990s, only for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus research.
The latest results of research to be presented in many Nature papers, according to the researchers, underscore not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also shows that neighboring planets have more common features with Earth than we had assumed," the ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds at the North Pole, the researchers also discovered in the south polar region a vortex formed by the clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the upper terrestrial atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as large.
This planet also called a sunrise star or evening star orbits the Sun for nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars does not closely resemble Earth, scientists take it as a basis that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets water had agglomerated which on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus dissociated into the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
