Von Beust receives in response negative criticism about the Olympics.
The mayor of Hamburg received much criticism from politics and the economy for not applying for the Summer Olympics.
Many want to continue fighting for competitions in the water sports section.
But Beust remembers that you have to be realistic when estimating the possibilities.
Hans-Joerg Schmidt-Trenz, director general of the Hamburg chamber of commerce, said Wednesday the resignation was "not good for the economic site".
In recent times no other project in the big city has fostered as much motivation as the idea of organizing the Olympic Games.
"Without this goal, we could not keep the political, sporting momentum at the same level."
Schmidt-Trenz demanded the Senate not to forget this project, but to find a new long-term application "which refers to another time".
Mayor Ole von Beust said on Wednesday that Hamburg's ambitions for the organization of the Summer Olympics would not be realized until at least 2028.
"Hamburg does not decide on the application for the Olympic Games, but the German Olympic Sports Federation decides," von Beust says in the WELT ONLINE.
He referred to the decision of the Sports Federation (Sportbund) expected in early December, on Munich's application for the 2028 Winter Olympics.
“This preference means for us that in this period of time, which until now we thought we had until 2028, from a realistic point of view we will have no chance.”
Despite everything, this dream did not end forever, von Beust said.
The Hamburg Sports Federation (HSB) regrets von Beut’s statements.
This gives the impression that in the next 25 years Hamburg does not want to apply for the Olympic Games.
“It’s too soon to let go of the opportunity, if at this point the plans are ruined,” HSB director Günter Ploß said on Wednesday.
A renunciation of the application is contradictory to the statement made by the head of the Senate at a reception on the occasion of the general meeting of the German Public Sport Federation of Higher Schools (adh).
There von Beust designated Hamburg's application for universities in 2015 not as a "replacement" of the Olympic Games in Hamburg.
Only last week the Sports Federation of Higher Schools named Hamburg as a candidate for the application.
The German Social Democratic Party (SPD-Bürgerschaftsfraktion) reproached the Senate for not taking such valuable time to build houses in Hamburg.
"For many years the Senate was delaying the development of the small neighborhood of Grasbrook, because this was in plans for the Olympics or the construction of houses," said Carola Veit and Jan Quast, deputies of the German Social Democratic Party (SPD).
While the SPD always demanded an integrated planning of Olympia for little Grasbrook and then the use of built houses, the CDU stressed the importance of entertainment.
At the time, Hamburg’s request for the 2012 Summer Olympics sparked great enthusiasm.
But Hamburg failed because of Leipzig.
It's not the wooden boxes.
Whoever links the terms Sweden and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but does not think of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently the wooden boxes produced in Sweden are like the shadow that weighs on the list of works of Warhol.
Most of the ninety-four Bright-Box "type" on this list are fake.
After a few months ago the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes, the Moderna Museet in Stockholm carried out internal investigations and reached disappointing conclusions: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former director of the Pontus Hultén museum gave to the Moderna Museet museum, are also fake, and almost a hundred others are in circulation.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confusing relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted the wooden boxes red, blue and white, with the same sample that had cartons of soap powder "Brillo".
According to Warhol, in the exhibition of his 1968 works in the Moderna Museet museum hundreds of Glitter-cardboard boxes were exhibited. These were not made by Warhol (due to expenses), but were brought directly from the cardboard factory of "Brillo".
These were not works of art, but examples (which were only objects) exhibited.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol allowed to produce in Sweden some Shine-wooden boxes, but they were not exhibited at the Modern Museet museum.
Witnesses of that time now speak of almost fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auctions as originals of the "Stockholm-type" "Brilliant-Boxes" authorized by Andy Warhol.
In auctions some of them were bought for more than $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous director of the Pontus Hultén museum made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden were produced and exposed almost one hundred of the wooden boxes that Warhol left him.
But in reality, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malmö for Hultén and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, the head of the curators of the Moderna Museet, investigated six Brillo-Boxes owned by the museum and also three of the Swedish private property that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm.
On the contrary, the structure of the 1990 copies shows that the paint was applied with a roller without directly printing the tightened silvers. Also it is not oil paint, but acrylic paint.
“These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and must be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol’s Brilliance-Boxes,” says Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet Museum and adds that if the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Commission in New York fails to reach any conclusions, the Moderna Museet Museum will classify these six boxes as copies/exhibition objects.
Already in July the Authentication Commission formally announced that it accepts these "serious accusations" in that they are soap powder boxes.
But from that moment everything remained silent.
The rebel soldiers surrender in Manila.
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers who had entrenched themselves in a hotel in Manila and had demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo have surrendered.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who blames the president for corruption and electoral fraud, told a reporter he could not answer for bloodshed.
Soldiers loyal to the government had stormed the hotel using tear gas.
Nearly two hundred soldiers had been entrenched in the building for a few hours.
Nearly half of them, including Trillanes, were on trial Thursday for having attempted a coup in 2003 that ended in failure.
He took advantage of the negotiations, to suddenly be able to deposit with about 30 sympathizers.
Obviously the military police officers who were to watch him had passed into his ranks and followed his mutiny.
They entered the "Peninsula" hotel and demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Government troops blocked the neighborhood around the Hotel Noble.
The president called for an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
Norberto Gonzales, the National Security Advisor, condemned the behavior of the soldiers.
“People are fed up,” Trillanes said.
“We invite people to join our ranks.”
Gen. Danilo Lim, who previously led the elite Scout Reangers troop, said that soon the other military troops wanted to follow suit.
Major government critics called for a major rally against the president on Thursday.
For months his government has been criticized for corruption.
In 2003 the financial district in Manila was a site that attracted all the attention due to the riot that was attempted against Arroyo.
The uprising failed after about 24 hours because the army wanted to participate.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against the democratically elected government in the Philippines.
United Internet will be the largest shareholder of Versatel.
United Internet secured more than 20 percent of the shares of telecommunications company Versatel.
